<div class="extra">
<h3>📌 Full Detailed Summary</h3>
<p>
The narrator, Charley, is a 31-year-old man living in New York. One day, while at Grand Central Station, he discovers a mysterious third level that seems to belong to the year 1894. Everything there looks old-fashioned: the people wear nineteenth-century clothes, the lights are gas lamps, and the furniture is antique. Charley is fascinated and excited about the possibility of escaping modern life and traveling to Galesburg, Illinois.
</p>
<p>
He goes to the ticket counter and asks for two tickets to Galesburg. However, the clerk refuses to accept his modern money. Frightened, Charley leaves and later shares his experience with his friend Sam, who is a psychiatrist. Sam suggests it may be a psychological escape, but later confirms that the third level exists when he travels there himself.
</p>
<p>
The story ends with this mysterious twist, making it unclear whether the third level is real or imaginary. It reflects human desire to escape, the fascination with the past, and the interplay between fantasy and reality.
</p>
